What Age Is the Best Age?
  





  Why Are Kentucky Police Destroying Pappy Van Winkle Bourbon?A sad day for bourbon fans.

Most Popular





Getty



By
Aaron Goldfarb


Jan 8, 2016












 



Bourbon brands aren't usually trending topics on Twitter and Facebook, nor do they often make the nightly news. But such was the case back in 2013 when 68 cases of the legendary Pappy Van Winkle were stolen. The Kentucky-based company was trending again last year when authorities took down a softball-playin', gun-totin', steroid-traffickin', organized crime ring and retrieved some of that stolen hooch. And here we find ourselves this week, talking about Pappy Van Winkle once more.Advertisement - Continue Reading BelowFirst came the news that the Franklin County Sheriff's Office would be auctioning off 28 of the recovered bottles. (Everyone celebrated!) Now comes the sad news that the Van Winkle family has asked a judge to have those bottles destroyed. And everyone cried, "WHY?!"Yet, I can't help thinking: All this talk over 28 measly bottles?Of course, this is no ordinary bourbon. Pappy Van Winkle has become the most famous whiskey in America, a unicorn unseen on store shelves for years, untasted by the vast majority of humans, and sold for astronomical sums on the secondary market. Those 28 bottles have a retail value of around $3,000 and a secondary value of perhaps $20,000, depending on age. That may sound like a lot, but it's not. I wouldn't be surprised if Buffalo Trace—the distiller of the Van Winkle line—washes that much whiskey down the drain every week.
Most PopularSo what's the big deal?"The whiskey lovers boo and the conspiracy theorists say the Van Winkles are loving the attention…again," explained acclaimed bourbon writer Fred Minnick.The Van Winkles are, if anything, masters at getting and then keeping their name (and their eponymous bourbon's name) in the headlines. I'm not claiming Julian Van Winkle III—grandson of Pappy and president of the Old Rip Van Winkle Distillery (note: not an actual distillery)—orchestrated this theft. But the outspoken man and his famed family have yet again taken a minor story and managed to keep it in the news cycle all week long.As always, these Pappy tales have absolutely nothing to do with the actual taste of the products. (My reviews: Pappy 15 Year is as world-class as bourbon comes, while the 20 and 23 Years suffer from an over-woodiness.) Instead, the story once again is about how rare this product is—though really not that rare, with about 100,000 bottles produced per year—and how every bottle lost is yet another bottle you will likely never taste.Of course, we can't ignore the fact that no one knows what the hell happened to those 28 bottles while they were out of Buffalo Trace's control."Where is the precedent for a sheriff's department auctioning alcohol or a controlled substance?" Minnick added, believing the bourbon should be destroyed. "How do we know the steroid-slinging, child porn-having criminals didn't tamper with the whiskey?"It's a valid point. Still, destroy it or not, I would bet the Van Winkles don't really care what happens to these 28 bottles. It won't affect their bottom line nor the perceived quality of their product. But ultimately, it will have more people writing about their bourbon, and arguing about it, and wondering just how good it truly is, and ultimately coveting it even more than they already do.Pappy Van Winkle may have been a great bourbon maker, but his grandson continues to be the P.T. Barnum of bourbon myth-making.More from Esquire:









 



